^-
{   Determining if You Should Explore for a Major Suit Fit   }
|FP||AT| 
As responder, it is easy to determine if you should explore for a major suit contract.|
PG| ***** 11 ***** |


AT|

If you do not hold at least four cards in either major, you should not bother to look for a
major suit fit. (On the few occasions when opener has a five-card major, you may miss a 5-3
fit, but most of the time NT will play just as well anyway.)|
PG| ***** 12 ***** |


AT|

If you do not have 4 or more cards in either major suit, your choices as responder are simple.|
PG| ***** 13 ***** |


AT|

With a minimum hand (seven points or less), pass.|
PG| ***** 14 ***** |


AT|

With a medium hand, bid 2NT. Partner should bid 3NT with a maximum NT hand (described earlier).|
PG| ***** 15 ***** |


AT|

With a maximum hand, bid 3NT.|
PG| ***** 16 ***** |


AT|

If, as responder, you have 4 or more cards in a major suit, you should use the |
