^-{Constructive Auctions after a NT Opening Bid}

{          Garbage Stayman          }
^-|HT|g|cp||FP||at|^b@2^z@3In general, it is usually easier to play in a suit than NT. This is particularly true when responder has a weak hand. Garbage Stayman was invented to allow the contract to be played in a suit at the 2 level when responder has a very weak hand (usually 4 or fewer points).|
PG| ***** 280 ***** |


HT|j|AT|

There are 2 variations:
* Classic Garbage Stayman
* Major Suit Garbage Stayman|
PG| ***** 281 ***** |


HT|j|AT|

There are 2 variations:
* Classic Garbage Stayman
* Major Suit Garbage Stayman

Classic Garbage Stayman works as follows. Responder has a weak hand with at least 4 diamonds and at least 3 cards in each major. Over 1N, responder bids 2@C. No matter what opener bids, responder passes. Therefore, the final contract will be either 2@D, 2@H, or 2@S.|
PG| ***** 282 ***** |


HT|j|AT|

There are 2 variations:
* Classic Garbage Stayman
* Major Suit Garbage Stayman

Classic Garbage Stayman works as follows. Responder has a weak hand with at least 4 diamonds and at least 3 cards in each major. Over 1N, responder bids 2@C. No matter what opener bids, responder passes. Therefore, the final contract will be either 2@D, 2@H, or 2@S.

Major Suit Garbage Stayman works as follows. Responder has a weak hand with at least 4-4 in the majors. Over 1N, responder bids 2C. If opener bids 2H or 2S, responder has an easy pass, and is playing in a 4-4 fit. If opener bids 2D, then responder bids 2@H. This tells opener that responder wants to play in either 2@H or 2@S. Opener passes with better hearts, and corrects to 2@S with better spades. The final contract is often a 7-card major suit fit (since the NT opener cannot have a doubleton in both hearts and spades), but this is usually better than playing 1N with a weak dummy.|
PG| ***** 283 ***** |


HT|j|AT|

There are 2 variations:
* Classic Garbage Stayman
* Major Suit Garbage Stayman

Classic Garbage Stayman works as follows. Responder has a weak hand with at least 4 diamonds and at least 3 cards in each major. Over 1N, responder bids 2C. No matter what opener bids, responder passes. Therefore, the final contract will be either 2@D, 2@H, or 2@S.

Major Suit Garbage Stayman works as follows. Responder has a weak hand with at least 4-4 in the majors. Over 1N, responder bids 2C. If opener bids 2@H or 2@S, responder has an easy pass, and is playing in a 4-4 fit. If opener bids 2D, then responder bids 2@H. This tells opener that responder wants to play in either 2@H or 2@S. Opener passes with better hearts, and corrects to 2@S with better spades. The final contract is often a 7-card major suit fit (since the NT opener cannot have a doubleton in both hearts and spades), but this is usually better than playing 1N with a weak dummy.

You can play both Classic and Major Suit Garbage Stayman simultaneously.
