^-{Constructive Auctions after a NT Opening Bid}

{          Weak NT Opening Bids          }
^-|HT|g|cp||FP||at|^b@2^z@3I like NT openings so much that I play 12-14 point 1NT openers, which means that I open many more hands 1NT than most people. I'm not sure why this treatment has not caught on more (most bridge players feel the strong NT has been ordained from on high!) because I think it has many advantages.|
PG| ***** 285 ***** |


AT|

Before I get into the advantages, let me explain how I show a strong NT. After opening a minor suit, I simply bid NT as my next bid (e.g. 1D-1S-1NT).|
PG| ***** 286 ***** |


AT|

The major advantage is that weak NTs lead to a more natural bidding style. For strong NT bidders, opening one of a minor can describe many different hand types, from a long suit to a minimum hand with NT distribution. With a weak NT, when I open 1 of a minor, I usually have a 5-card suit (with a 4-card suit I would open 1NT). Also, the weak NT has pre-emptive value; responder knows a lot about opener's hand and where we should play the contract, but the opponents are somewhat in the dark, having to bid at the 2 level in order to get into the auction.|
PG| ***** 287 ***** |


AT|

Clearly, the point values for responder's hand change accordingly:|
