^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Okay, let's get started. Welcome to my second class on Fundamentals of Constructive Bidding. The purpose of these classes is to teach you the fundamentals behind most popular bidding systems. Many people memorize rules of bidding but do not understand why those rules were invented. Hopefully, after these classes, you will understand the whys and therefore will be able to figure out what to bid, rather than memorizing a bunch of rules. Tonight's lesson is on auctions starting with 1NT. Auctions when the opening bid is 1N are usually pretty straight forward. Those who attended the last lesson remember the concept of the "captain of the bidding."|
PG| ***** 463 ***** |


at|

To briefly review, in every auction, one person is "captain", the other is "subordinate." It is the job of the captain to determine the final contract, both level and strain. The captain does this by asking his or her partner "questions" about their hand. It is the job of the subordinate partner to answer those questions. On many auctions, responder is the captain. On hands where the opening bid is 1NT, this is particularly true. Once you open 1NT, your partner is responsible for placing the final contract.|
PG| ***** 464 ***** |


at|

Because 1NT is such a descriptive bid, that is usually pretty easy to do. Please, remember, if your partner opens 1NT, you are in charge of making sure you get to the right contract. Further, because 1NT is such a descriptive bid, you should open it whenever possible. Most people play a 1NT opener shows 15-17 HCP, and one of 3 distributions: 4-3-3-3 4-4-3-2 or 5-3-3-2. Another way to say this is your hand can have at most one doubleton. There is a tendency by some people to stretch the distributions on occasion and open 1N with 6-3-2-2 and perhaps 5-4-2-2. But I personally don't care to do that. However, one thing that I highly recommend is that you open 1NT even with a 5 card major. Most experts agree with that. When you have a 15-17 point balanced hand, it is very difficult to get your points across if you open 1H or 1S.|
PG| ***** 465 ***** |


NT||
ht|e|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|When the auction often goes 1H/1S-P-1N, you can bid 2N, but that will often get you too high. So, because 1N is so descriptive, opening 1N with a 5 card major is preferable. Some people worry about missing a major suit fit. The only time that is even an issue is when partner has exactly 3 card support in the 5 card major. With 4 card support, partner would bid Stayman. Obviously,, it is possible to miss a 5-3 fit, but most of the time NT plays as well as the 5-3 fit.|
PG| ***** 466 ***** |


at|

Now let's talk about responder. If you remember from last time, responder can classify his hand as one of three categories-- minimum response, medium response, or maximum response. The only difference from the last lesson is the point counts for these classifications is different. A minimum response hand is 7 points or less. If responder has a minimum hand, game is not possible, so the idea is to stay as low as you can. You will either play in 1NT or 2 of a major. So, with a minimum hand, the idea is to get out ASAP.|
PG| ***** 467 ***** |


at|

A medium hand is 8 or 9 points. If responder has a medium hand, game is possible, but only if opener has a maximum NT opener. I will define what a maximum NT opener is in a few minutes. But the point is, with a medium hand, responder invites game, and opener accepts with a maximum. If responder has 10 or more points, then he or she has a maximum response. In that case, responder is responsible for making sure their side gets to game. With a maximum hand, responder must NEVER make a bid that opener can pass.|
PG| ***** 468 ***** |


at|

It is time to talk about opener's hand categories. For NT openers, since the range is so narrow, there are only two categories:
a minimum NT opener, and a maximum NT opener. The only time it is important for opener to distinguish is when responder makes an invitational bid. If responder makes an invitational bid, opener goes to game with a maximum NT hand. A max NT hand meets one of the following criteria
 -- any 17 point hand
 -- any 16 HCP hand with a fit for partner's major
 -- any 16 HCP hand with a 5 card suit
 -- any 16 HCP with at two or more 10s and 9s and not 4-3-3-3 distribution.|
PG| ***** 469 ***** |


NT||ht|e|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Okay, now that we know when we should bid game, let's talk about what strain (suit or NT) to choose. One important rule to remember is, it is fairly rare that you would rather play 5 of a minor than 3NT. I won't say it never happens that you want to play 5 of a minor, but too many people bypass 3NT when they should be there. It is usually much harder to take 11 tricks than 9 tricks. So, your mind set should be, you want to play either 3NT or 4 of a major. You almost never want to play 5 of a minor. Therefore, responder's job in defining which suit to play in is simply to determine if there is the possibility of a major suit fit.|
PG| ***** 470 ***** |


AT|

If there is no possibility of a major suit fit, then responder should place the contract in the appropriate level of NT. Responder should look for a major suit fit if he or she has 4 or more cards in at least one of the major suits. Otherwise responder should assume the contract will be in NT. As responder, if you do not have a 4+ card major, your choices are simple.
With a minimum hand, pass.
With a medium hand, invite by bidding 2N
With a maximum hand, bid 3N. It is pretty simple. Don't worry about shortness or long minors. If you have the right number of HCP bid 3NT or 2NT. You will occasionally be wrong, but most of the time you will do fine.|
PG| ***** 471 ***** |


AT|

What do responders do if they have a 4+ card major. There are two conventions that take care of finding out whether or not to play in a major. They are Stayman and Jacoby Transfers. You should bid Stayman under the following circumstances:
a) You have a medium or maximum hand. I will talk about a possible exception to this later, but for now, assume you cannot bid Stayman with a minimum. You have one 4-card major, 2 four-card majors, or one 4-card major and one 5-card major. Those are the only distributions where you should bid Stayman.|
PG| ***** 472 ***** |


AT|

Basically, Stayman is defined to find a 4-4 major fit. If you have more than 4 cards in a major, you generally should use Jacoby Transfers. The only exception being when you are exactly 5/4 in the majors. As most of you know, I am sure, a 2@C response to 1NT is the Stayman convention. When responder bids 2C, he or she is saying nothing about clubs. Responder is simply asking if opener has a 4-card major. If opener has a 4 card major, he or she bids that major. If opener does not have a 4-card major, the response is 2@D. With two 4-card majors, most people play that opener bids 2@H.|
PG| ***** 473 ***** |


NT||nt||ht|e|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Okay, let's first talk about what responder does with a maximum hand. If opener does not show a one of responder's 4 card majors, then responder simply bids 3NT. If opener shows one of responder's 4 card majors, then responder bids 4 of that major. That's it. Opener almost always respects responder's final decision. There is one exception. If opener has two 4-card majors, then opener knows that there has to be a 4-4 major fit. Responder should never bid Stayman without a 4-card major. Therefore, if responder bids Stayman, and opener has 2 4-card majors, there has to be a 4-4 fit.|
PG| ***** 474 ***** |


AT|

So, if the auction goes 1N-2@C-2@H-3N. Opener knows that responder must have 4 spades. Responder bid Stayman showing a 4-card major. If the 4-card major is not hearts, it has to be spades. So, if opener has two 4-card majors, he or she is allowed to override responder's decision to bid 3N, and bid 4S. That is the only case where that is true, when opener has two 4-card majors.|
PG| ***** 475 ***** |


AT|

With a medium hand, responder does one of the following. If opener bids a 4-card major that responder has, responder raises to 3 of the major. Otherwise, responder bids 2N. Opener should bid game with a maximum hand, as I defined before. If responder invites in 3 of a major, opener should go with 16-17 points. If responder invites with 2N, then opener should go with a maximum hand, using the criteria I defined before. And, if opener has 2 four-card majors, and the auction goes 1N-2@C-2@H-2N. Then opener should correct to 3@S with a min hand (15 HCP) and bid 4S with a max hand. That's it for Stayman. I said a lot, but the principles are pretty simple. Responder invites with a medium hand, bids game with a maximum hand, and opener accepts an invitation with a maximum hand.|
PG| ***** 476 ***** |


AT|

Finally, let's talk about Jacoby transfers. Jacoby transfers are used by responder when he or she has a 5+ card major. Pretty much any time responder has a 5-card major, responder should bid a Jacoby Transfer, regardless of strength (even with a min). The only exception (and it is fairly rare) is if responder has exactly 5/4 in the majors and a medium or maximum response. Then responder should use Stayman. But virtually all of the time, responder should use Jacoby with a 5+ card major. So, when partner opens 1N and you have a 5+ card major, your first instinct should be to use a Jacoby transfer.|
PG| ***** 477 ***** |


NT||nt||ht|e|AT|
Let's briefly review the mechanics of the convention, although I am sure most of you know it. If you have 5+ hearts responders bid 2@D. This obligates opener to bid 2@H. You have "transferred" the heart contract from your hand to opener's hand even though you have hearts you want opener to be declarer. There are a number of theoretical reasons why this is a good thing. But don't worry about them for now. Just remember you have to use a transfer with a 5+ card major.|
PG| ***** 478 ***** |


AT|

Similarly, if you have spades, you, as responder bid 2@H. This obligates opener to bid 2@S. That's it for the most part. There are extensions to Jacoby Transfers, but for this lesson I am not going to worry about them. Here, I am going to stick with the simple 2@D forces 2@H and 2@H forces 2@S. On most hands, that is what should happen.|
PG| ***** 479 ***** |


AT|

Once responder forces opener to accept the transfer, what should responder do? With a minimum hand, the answer is easy
just pass. If responder has a weak hand, playing in responder's 5-card suit (even with a 5-2 fit) is almost always better than playing in 1NT. So, if you have a weak hand and a 5-card major, make a Jacoby transfer intending to pass opener's response.|
PG| ***** 480 ***** |


AT|

What would you do with a maximum hand? If responder has a maximum (10+ HCP), their side must be in game. The only question is, which game. If responder has a six-card major, then their side must have at least an 8 card fit (opener must have at least a doubleton). So, responder should just bid 4 of the major. With a 5-card major, responder is not sure whether to play 3N or 4 of the major. So, responder bids 3N. Some people claim this is a "shut out" bid. Those people are wrong, lol. 3NT by responder, after a transfer, is giving opener a choice of games.|
PG| ***** 481 ***** |


AT|

With a doubleton in the major, opener passes, with 3 or more in the major, opener bids 4 of the major. Please, remember, the auction 1N-2@H-2@S-3N is not a shut out. It is a choice between 3N and 4@S.|
PG| ***** 482 ***** |


AT|

What about with a medium hand? The choices are similar to what you do with a max hand, but at a lower level. If responder has a six card major, responder should invite by bidding 3 of the major. Opener should accept with a max hand, or 3 or more cards in the major even with 15 HCP, if opener has 3 cards in the major suit, with a known 9 card fit, opener should accept. For example, if the auction goes 1N-2@D-2@H-3@H, opener should bid 4@H with any hand that has 3 or more hearts. And should also bid 4@H even with a doubleton heart, with a maximum hand, as defined before.|
PG| ***** 483 ***** |


NT||nt||ht|e|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|One good general bidding principle to remember is 9 card fits are very powerful. So, you should tend to be more aggressive with a 9 card fit. If partner invites game (in any auction) and you know you have a 9 card major suit fit, you should accept the invitation. Similarly, you should be conservative with an 8 card fit. If partner invites and you know you only have an 8 card fit, you should tend to not bid a close game. That principle applies to all auctions not just NT auctions.|
PG| ***** 484 ***** |


AT|

Okay, back to Jacoby transfers. The only thing left is when responder has a medium hand and a 5 card major. In that case, responder bids 2N over the transfer. For example, the auction 1N-2@D-2@H-2N says the following. Responder has exactly 5 hearts and 8 or 9 points. Opener can now easily figure out what to do. With a doubleton and a minimum hand, pass. With 3 card support, and a minimum hand, correct to 3 of the major. With a minimum hand and 4 card support, bid 4 of the major (known 9 card fit). With a max hand and a doubleton, opener bids 3N. And with a maximum hand and 3+ card support, opener bids 4 of the major. That's pretty much it.|
PG| ***** 485 ***** |


AT|

You can have some complicated auctions with transfers. But for now, I suggest you keep things simple, until you get the basics down. Most of the time, you will do fine with the simple approach. One small comment about Texas Transfers. Most people on BBO play that with a maximum response and a 6 card major, you transfer at the 4 level. In other words, the auction 1N-4D means responder has 6+ hearts and a maximum hand. Responder is telling opener to bid 4H. Similarly, the auction 1N-4H shows responder has a maximum with 6+ spades. There is nothing wrong with playing Texas, but it is also unnecessary.|
PG| ***** 486 ***** |


AT|

Experts differentiate between the following two auctions: 1N-2@H-2@S-4@S and 1N-4@H-4@S. But most non-experts do not differentiate. If you do not differentiate between those 2 auctions then there is no reason to play Texas. However, there is no reason not to play it either, unless partner forgets the convention :). Okay, lets do a few quiz hands. Assume partner opens 1NT. I will give you a hand. You need to determine two things. The first thing is: is the hand a minimum, medium, or maximum response. The second thing is: what do you bid, both initially, and after hearing opener's rebid. On any auction where partner opens 1N, this is what your thinking process should be. First, determine your hand strength. Second, figure out not only your first bid, but the follow ups to opener's possible rebids. Next is hand 1.|
PG| ***** 487 ***** |


