AT|
It is a minimum hand. Therefore, you want to get out ASAP. But, you would rather play in a 5 card suit than 1N. So, you bid 2@D, transfer to hearts, and plan on passing the forced 2H bid. Don't worry about the spade suit.|
PG| ***** 491 ***** |


AT|
 
@SKxxx @HKxxx @DQxx @Cxx|
PG| ***** 492 ***** |


AT|
The hand is medium. Since you have at least one 4-card majors, you should bid Stayman. Bid 2@C. If partner shows a major suit you raise to 3, asking him or her to bid 4 with a maximum NT. If partner bids 2@D over 2@C, you bid 2N, asking partner to bid 3N with a maximum NT opener.|
PG| ***** 493 ***** |


AT|

@SQxx @HKxxxx @DKxx @Cxx|
PG| ***** 494 ***** |


AT|
This is medium. You also have a 5 card major, so Jacoby is appropriate. Bid 2@D. Over partner's forced 2@H response, bid 2N. Remember, that shows you have exactly 5 hearts and a medium hand. It is giving partner a choice of contracts. With a minimum hand and a doubleton, pard passes. With a minimum hand and 3 hearts, pard bids 3@H. With a minimum hand and 4-card support, pard bids 4@H (9 card fit). With a maximum hand and a doubleton, pard bids 3N. With a maximum hand and 3+ hearts, pard bids 4@H. Again, if you understand the concepts, figuring out what to bid is a matter of deduction, not memorizing rules.|
PG| ***** 495 ***** |


AT|

@SKQxx @HKxxxx @Dxx @Cxx
This is the rare hand where, because you are exactly 5/4 in the majors, and have a medium or max hand, you bid Stayman. Bid 2@C. If partner responds 2@D, you bid 2@H. That shows 5 hearts and 4 spades. If partner bids 2H, I would bid 4@H (9 card fit), although that is aggressive. And if partner bids 2@S, I would bid 3@S, inviting pard to bid 4@S with a maximum.|
